Stepwise approach (pipeline + evaluation)
Below is a clear, ordered checklist you can paste into your report or use as your
implementation plan. I split it into Pipeline steps (what runs at inference) and
Evaluation / validation steps (what you run during development & before deployment).
Pipeline steps (inference / runtime)
1. Receive user query
o Record metadata (timestamp, user id if applicable, session context).
2. Self-RAG controller: initial assessment
o LLM inspects the raw query and decides which sub-pipeline(s) to run:
direct retrieval, HYDE, multi-query retrieval, query decomposition, or
some combination.
o Also decides confidence thresholds and allowed cost budget for this
request.
3. If query is vague → HYDE
o Use LLM to generate a rich hypothetical document (semantic expansion)
that captures intended meaning.
o Embed the HYDE document and use it as a retrieval query.
4. If query could have multiple interpretations → Multi-Query Retrieval
o Generate several paraphrases/alternate queries (cover synonyms, layman
vs. clinical language, common misspellings).
o Embed each paraphrase and perform retrieval for each.
5. If query is multi-step / multi-intent → Query Decomposition
o Split into sequential sub-questions (e.g., symptoms → causes; drug A
interactions → dosing).
o For each sub-question: retrieve + (optionally) answer; keep intermediate
results for synthesis.
6. If query is straightforward → Direct retrieval
o Embed original query and retrieve top-k documents (sparse/dense
retriever depending on design).
7. Aggregate retrieved documents into a Document Pool
o Merge and deduplicate results from HYDE, multi-query, decomposition,
and direct retrieval.
o Keep provenance metadata (source url/id, retrieval score, which subquery produced it).
8. Re-ranking / precision filtering
o Run a stronger re-ranker (cross-encoder / domain-adapted model) to
score and select the most relevant and reliable documents.
o Optionally apply heuristics for authority (prioritize guidelines, PubMed,
FDA, clinical reviews).
9. Self-RAG reflection / iterative retrieval loop (optional)
o The LLM inspects the top results and asks: “Is confidence sufficient?”
o If not, trigger targeted extra retrieval (rerun with different paraphrase,
expand context, or search a different collection).
o Stop when a confidence threshold is met or budget is exhausted.
10.Answer generation (RAG)
o LLM synthesizes the final response grounded on re-ranked documents.
o Provide explicit citations and provenance snippets for each assertion
(quote or paraphrase + source).
11. Safety & clinical guardrails
o Run safety filters: check for hallucinated claims, disallowed medical
advice words, and ensure disclaimers (e.g., “not a medical professional” /
“see your doctor”) where appropriate.
o If high-risk or low-confidence, escalate to a human-in-the-loop flag.
12.Return response + logging
o Return answer + cited sources + confidence score and optionally a short
explanation of why certain sources were chosen.
o Log retrieval IDs, re-ranker scores, LLM reasoning trace (for auditing).
Evaluation & validation steps (development + pre-deployment)
1. Define evaluation goals & datasets
o Create/collect: held-out test set (medical QAs), development set, and a
human-eval set.
o Include diverse query types: vague lay queries, technical clinician
queries, multi-intent, and adversarial/noisy queries.
o Include gold annotations (correct answers and relevant documents).
2. Automatic retrieval + end-to-end metrics (use RAGAS)
o Run RAGAS (or equivalent RAG-specific framework) to evaluate percomponent and end-to-end:
▪ Retriever recall@k, precision@k, MRR.
▪ Faithfulness / grounding rate (percent of claims supported by
retrieved docs).
▪ Generation relevance and answer correctness.
▪ Noise ratio / irrelevant content rate.
o Use RAGAS outputs to find weak components (bad retriever, poor reranker, generator hallucination).
3. LLM/evaluator based checks (DeepEval / Grouse)
o Run general LLM evaluators to measure fluency, coherence, and
toxicity/bias.
o Use these to ensure output readability and non-harmful phrasing.
4. Task-specific benchmark tests (Med QA datasets)
o Evaluate on medical benchmarks such as MedQA / PubMedQA / other
clinically-relevant partitions to measure accuracy / EM / F1 where
applicable.
5. Human expert evaluation (clinical review)
o Have clinicians or domain experts rate outputs for: clinical correctness,
safety, clarity, and actionability.
o Use a rubric (e.g., correct/partially correct/incorrect, harmful/benign).
o Calculate inter-annotator agreement to validate rubric reliability.
6. Hallucination & faithfulness analysis
o Measure hallucination rate (claims not present in retrieved docs).
o For high-impact errors, trace which pipeline stage introduced the error
(retrieval vs. re-ranking vs. generation).
7. Ablation studies
o Turn components on/off to quantify their value: HYDE vs. no HYDE, multiquery vs. single query, with/without re-ranking, Self-RAG controller vs.
always-run-full-pipeline.
o Report delta in both accuracy and cost.
8. Robustness & adversarial tests
o Test with noisy input (typos, mixed languages), ambiguous phrasing, and
intentional adversarial queries.
o Ensure confidence calibration and safe failures.
9. Human-in-the-loop simulations
o Simulate scenarios where the system escalates to a clinician. Measure
false positives/negatives of escalation flags.
10. Operational metrics & monitoring plan
o Define production KPIs: latency, throughput, cost per request, grounding
rate, user-reported accuracy, escalation rate.
o Set alerts for regressions (sudden drop in grounding rate or spike in
hallucinations).
11.Bias & safety audit
o Run specialized checks for demographic bias, harmful instructions, and
regulatory compliance.
o Document limitations and explicit failure modes.
12. Continuous evaluation + feedback loop
o Periodically (weekly/monthly) re-evaluate on fresh queries, retrain
reranker/embeddings if drift observed.
o Use logged user feedback and clinician corrections to update index and
models.
Metrics to report (recommended)
• Retriever: Recall@k, MRR, Precision@k
• Re-ranker: NDCG, Precision@k
• End-to-end: Accuracy / EM / F1 (on QA), Faithfulness / Grounding rate,
Hallucination rate
• Human eval: % clinically correct, safety score, clarity score, inter-annotator
agreement (κ)
• Operational: Latency, Cost per query, Escalation rate
